metadata.name: Dido to Aeneas
metadata.description:
O for thee to be as to the wind; ingress,  

Be changed as time doth flow — unless  

Thy skin were like the oaken bark, or steel:  

Unearthed; hardened beyond Time’s wheel. 

What worsed path could be thy pick, if thou  
  
Were daft, and ne’er knew th’ Tempest’s maw  

Or mounting sea. O, for a soul as brave  

As thine, to trust the damning awful wave, 
 
And bore, whose blows thz heart hath felt afore. 

Think not, my love, th’ nearing lee shore, 

Nor mine eyes e’ermore. Rather estrange 
 
Thy gaze below. Behold! — thyself, seachanged.
